{{about|the American Book Company established in 1890|the American Book Company established in 1996|American Book Company (1996)}}
{{Infobox publisher | image = [[File:American Book Company mark.jpg|250px|American Book Company publisher's mark]] | parent = | status = Defunct | founded = 1890 | founder = [[Van Antwerp, Bragg and Co.]], [[Alfred Smith Barnes#A.S. Barnes & Co.|A.S. Barnes & Co.]], [[D. Appleton and Co.]], and [[Ivison, Blakeman and Co.]] | successor = [[D. C. Heath and Company]] | country = [[United States]] | headquarters = | distribution = | keypeople = | publications = [[book]]s | topics = | genre = | imprints = | revenue = | numemployees = | nasdaq = | url = }}The '''American Book Company''' (ABC) was an educational book [[publisher]] in the [[United States]] that specialized in [[elementary school]], [[secondary school]] and collegiate-level [[textbook]]s. It is best known for publishing the [[McGuffey Readers]], which sold 120 million copies between 1836 and 1960.<ref>{{cite web| title = McGuffey Readers World| publisher = The Paradigm Company| url = http://www.mcguffeyreaders.com/history.htm| accessdate = 2008-04-17}}</ref>
==History== [[File:American book company 1916. letter envelope-2.JPG|thumb|left|150px|American Book Company, letter envelope 25 September 1916]] American Book Company was formed in 1890 by the consolidation of [[Van Antwerp, Bragg and Co.]], [[Alfred Smith Barnes#A.S. Barnes & Co.|A.S. Barnes & Co.]], [[D. Appleton and Co.]], and [[Ivison, Blakeman and Co.]]<ref>{{cite web| title = American Book Company Records| publisher = [[Syracuse University]] Library| url = http://library.syr.edu/digital/guides/a/amer_book_co.htm}}</ref> It was acquired by [[Litton Industries]] in 1967<ref>{{cite journal| title = American Literature in the Marketplace. Literature and Cultural Inquiry.| last = Betsky| first = Seymour| journal = Higher Education Quarterly| volume = 37| issue = 4| pages = 320–340| publisher = [[Blackwell Publishing]]| date = September 1983| url = http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-2273.1983.tb02009.x| doi = 10.1111/j.1468-2273.1983.tb02009.x}}</ref> and existed as a division of Litton Educational Publishing, Inc. until being sold to the [[Thomson Organization|International Thomson Organization]] in the late seventies. Thomson then sold its American Book Company [[K-12]] assets to [[D. C. Heath and Company]] in 1981. The company was absorbed into D. C. Heath and ceased to exist as an [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]]. Any remaining K-12 assets of the American Book Company are now owned by [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] Publishing Company, which acquired D. C. Heath and Company in 1995.
Many of the college level textbook rights of ABC/Litton were sold by International Thomson as well, to [[Van Nostrand Reinhold]], though some<ref>{{cite web| title = Great Traditions in Ethics| work = Amazon.com| url = https://www.amazon.com/Traditions-Introduction-Theodore-Sheldon-Peterfreund/dp/B000OS76SC| accessdate = 2008-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Great Traditions in Ethics| publisher = Cengage Learning| url = http://academic.cengage.com/cengage/instructor.do?&disciplinenumber=5&product_isbn=9780495094982&contextelement=http://academic.cengage.com/cengage| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080418060008/http://academic.cengage.com/cengage/instructor.do| archivedate = 2008-04-18| df = }}</ref> remained under the [[Cengage Learning|Wadsworth]] imprint at Thomson, which is now [[Cengage Learning]].
