{{Multiple issues| {{Underlinked|date=August 2016}} {{Orphan|date=August 2016}} {{notability|Web|date=April 2015}} }}
{{Infobox website | name = Open Rev. | logo = [[File:Open Rev. Icon.svg|120px|borderless]] | screenshot = | url = {{URL|openrev.org}} | type = [[Social software|Social software for academic research]] | language = English | content_license = Attribution Share-Alike Unported | author = Erik Bauch and Georg Kucsko | launch_date = Aug 2014<ref>{{cite web | title=We've launched | author=Open Rev. Blog | date=Aug 2014 | url=http://openrev.org/blog/newsletters-aug-2014-weve-launched}}</ref> }}
'''Open Rev.''' is a web-based platform for open discussion and annotation of research publications and related material. Researchers can comment directly on text, formulas, and images in research papers, post related questions and answer questions posed by each other. Open Rev's web-based PDF viewer has been implemented to encourage public discussion and [[open peer review]] of scientific publications. User contributions are licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported.<ref>https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/us/</ref>
Open Rev. was a participant of the Harvard i-Lab Venture Incubation Program 2014<ref>{{cite web | title=Harvard i-Lab Website | author=Harvard innovation Lab | url=http://i-lab.harvard.edu/venture-incubation/resident-teams/open-review}}</ref> and has won awards from the Harvard Institute for Learning and Teaching<ref>{{cite web | title=HILT Spark Grant awards announced | author=HILT | url=http://hilt.harvard.edu/news/hilt-spark-grant-awards-announced}}</ref> and Education Innovation Pitch Competition.<ref>{{cite web | title=Recent Pitch Winners | author=Education Innovation Pitch Competition Announcement | url=https://sites.google.com/site/bridgeathgse/home/education-innovation-pitch-competition/previous-competitions}}</ref>
== History == Open Rev. was created by Erik Bauch and Georg Kucsko, currently PhD candidates in the Harvard Physics program, to foster public and open discussions on research papers. It officially launched in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | title=We've launched | author=Open Rev. Blog | date=Aug 2014 | url=http://openrev.org/blog/newsletters-aug-2014-weve-launched}}</ref> As of 2015, the user base has risen to over 1000 participants and includes institutions such as Harvard, MIT, Northeastern University, Royal Holloway University of London, and Uppsala Universitet.
== Media == Open Rev. has been featured in Harvard Physics,<ref>{{cite web | title=Introducing Open Rev! | author=Harvard Physics Announcement | date=Aug 2014 | url=https://www.physics.harvard.edu/node/372}}</ref> the Harvard Gazette<ref>{{cite web | title=Physics students introduce open, collaborative annotation tool | author=Harvard Gazette News+ | date=Aug 2014 | url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/newsplus/physics-students-introduce-open-collaborative-annotation-tool/}}</ref> and the Harvard alumni magazine, Colloquy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gsas.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/pdfs/issues/colloquy_fall14.pdf|title=Taking Open Access to a New Level|last=|first=|date=Fall 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=|author=Harvard Colloquy, p.6}}</ref> In an interview in Colloquy, co-founder Erik Bauch explained, “Up until now scientific discussions usually occurred at conferences, in journal club, or in hallways on the way to lunch. With Open Rev. we are trying to motivate people to take some of these discussions online and share their knowledge with the whole scientific community.”
== Features == * public commenting and Q&A on PDF papers * private groups with tagging and discussions * public groups to share papers by topic * web-based PDF viewer with PDF search capability * rate papers, comments and replies * Latex and Markdown support * picture upload * anonymous commenting * automatic extraction of metadata from PDFs * tagging of PDFs * import papers from [http://www.arxiv.org arXiv]
