'''Summer melt''' is the phenomenon of prospective [[college]] students' [[motivation]] to attend college "melting" away during the summer between the end of high school and beginning of college.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ed.gov/blog/2013/07/summer-melt/ |title=Summer Melt |last1=Ceja |first1=Alejandra |last2= |first2= |date=July 2013 |website=Homeroom |publisher=[[United States Department of Education]] |accessdate=January 19, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120073459/http://www.ed.gov/blog/2013/07/summer-melt/ |archivedate=January 20, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=twsLATimes>LARRY GORDON, October 19, 2014, Los Angeles Times [http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-college-melt-20141020-story.html Advisors work to freeze 'summer melt,' get students to college], Retrieved January 19, 2015</ref><ref name=twsCSMonitor>Stacy Teicher Khadaroo, AUGUST 8, 2014, Christian Science Monitor, [http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Education/2014/0808/Stopping-summer-melt-and-getting-more-kids-to-college-this-fall Stopping 'summer melt' – and getting more kids to college this fall], Retrieved January 19, 2015</ref><ref name=twsWashPost>Peg Tyre, August 29, 2013, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/she-the-people/wp/2013/08/29/why-some-students-are-no-shows-on-the-first-day-of-college/ Why some students are no-shows on the first day of college], Retrieved January 19, 2015</ref><ref name=twsTime>Annie Murphy Paul, May 24, 2013, Time Magazine, [http://ideas.time.com/2013/05/24/the-summer-before-college-is-critical-to-success/ The Key to College Success: Summer -- Incoming freshmen can flounder in the months before becoming a college student], Retrieved January 19, 2015</ref> This phenomenon is especially prevalent in low-income [[minority group|minority]] communities, where students who qualify for college and in some cases even register for classes ultimately end up not attending college because they lack resources, support, guidance, and encouragement.<ref name=twsSJMercury>Jennifer Andaluz, San Jose Mercury News, August 14, 2014, [http://www.mercurynews.com/opinion/ci_26336333/summer-melt-low-income-kids-accepted-college-need Summer melt: Low income kids accepted to college need help to actually get there], Retrieved January 19, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite interview |last=Vedantam |first=Shankar |subject-link= |interviewer=Greene, David |title=Why Poor Students' College Plans 'Melt' Over The Summer |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/07/16/202566709/why-poor-students-college-plans-are-hijacked-over-the-summer |date=July 16, 2013 |work=[[NPR]] |access-date=January 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>Castleman, B. L., & Page, L. C. (2013). Can Text Messages Mitigate Summer Melt?. New England Journal of Higher Education, 2.</ref> Support programs, particularly by colleges using nudge methods like messaging students via text message, have been found to reduce summer melt.<ref>Castleman, B. L., Page, L. C., & Schooley, K. (2014). The Forgotten Summer: Does the Offer of College Counseling after High School Mitigate Summer Melt among College-Intending, Low-Income High School Graduates?. Journal of Policy Analysis and Management, 33(2), 320-344.</ref><ref>Castleman, B. L., Owen, L., & Page, L. C. (2016). Reprint of “Stay late or start early? Experimental evidence on the benefits of college matriculation support from high schools versus colleges”. Economics Of Education Review, 51113-124.</ref><ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-admissions-officers-wont-just-chill-about-summer-melt-1502468367</ref>
